sign casts anymore?

111
00:07:39,526 --> 00:07:41,894
Not really.

112
00:07:41,961 --> 00:07:43,829
And this is what
you have to wear?

113
00:07:43,897 --> 00:07:45,898
Yeah, sixth grade.

114
00:07:45,965 --> 00:07:47,766
Coming down the street, I
thought maybe you'd become

115
00:07:47,834 --> 00:07:49,601
a lawyer
or something.

116
00:07:50,804 --> 00:07:53,205
So, how's sixth grade?

117
00:07:53,273 --> 00:07:55,708
You know, now I'm the youngest
in middle school,

118
00:07:55,775 --> 00:07:59,111
instead of the oldest in lower,
so... you know, it's cool.

119
00:07:59,179 --> 00:08:01,113
You mean, you're
picked on a bit?

120
00:08:01,181 --> 00:08:02,681
Yeah, sometimes.

121
00:08:02,749 --> 00:08:05,117
Is that how you got
your hand busted?

122
00:08:05,185 --> 00:08:07,152
Nuh-uh.
I just fell.

123
00:08:09,422 --> 00:08:14,293
Okay, well, uh... don't pick
back too much, okay?

124
00:08:14,361 --> 00:08:15,728
I got a letter for you.

125
00:08:15,795 --> 00:08:17,796
Oh, that's great, Gulls.
You know that I had to

126
00:08:17,864 --> 00:08:19,431
look up "Cotillion"
from your last one.

127
00:08:19,499 --> 00:08:20,766
Yeah? That's horrible.

128
00:08:20,834 --> 00:08:24,303
So, what else... what else
is middle school like?

129
00:08:24,371 --> 00:08:26,705
Well, it's
kind of the same.

130
00:08:26,773 --> 00:08:29,708
It's boring. I have to read
<i>Johnny Tremain.</i>

131
00:08:29,776 --> 00:08:31,844
What's that about?

132
00:08:31,911 --> 00:08:33,712
This kid who makes silver bowls
with Paul Revere

133
00:08:33,780 --> 00:08:35,781
and gets his hand burned.

134
00:08:35,849 --> 00:08:38,817
You like it?

135
00:08:38,885 --> 00:08:40,352
It's okay. Not really.

136
00:08:40,420 --> 00:08:41,687
I can't finish it.

137
00:08:41,755 --> 00:08:44,390
Yeah, and anyway,
silversmithing

138
00:08:44,457 --> 00:08:47,192
will probably get in the
way of your lawyering.

139
00:08:47,260 --> 00:08:48,527
Yeah.

140
00:08:51,731 --> 00:08:53,165
How's your dad and Ellen?

141
00:08:53,233 --> 00:08:55,501
Fine.

142
00:08:55,568 --> 00:08:57,736
Yeah, you like her
any better now?

143
00:08:57,804 --> 00:08:59,238
She's okay.

144
00:08:59,305 --> 00:09:00,572
She's a pretty good cook,

145
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:03,709
but she gets angry
about the weirdest things.

146
00:09:03,777 --> 00:09:05,444
Like what?

147
00:09:05,512 --> 00:09:08,347
Like sometimes, after
I wash my hands,

148
00:09:08,415 --> 00:09:09,982
she says I leave
the soap dirty.

149
00:09:10,050 --> 00:09:11,250
What does that mean?

150
00:09:11,317 --> 00:09:13,752
I know. It means I'm supposed
to wash the soap

151
00:09:13,820 --> 00:09:16,388
after I wash my hands.

152
00:09:16,456 --> 00:09:17,990
(giggling)

153
00:09:18,058 --> 00:09:19,525
Well...

154
00:09:19,592 --> 00:09:24,396
But sometimes when she talks to
her friends, she says things.

155
00:09:24,464 --> 00:09:25,864
Like what?

156
00:09:25,932 --> 00:09:28,934
Like once I heard her say--
about you, I guess--

157
00:09:29,002 --> 00:09:33,372
that they wanted you
to get a... annulment?

158
00:09:33,440 --> 00:09:34,940
That who wanted?

159
00:09:35,008 --> 00:09:37,943
I guess Dad and Grandma.

160
00:09:38,011 --> 00:09:39,445
Oh.

161
00:09:39,512 --> 00:09:41,447
And I asked Eric
Muftie what that was,

162
00:09:41,514 --> 00:09:43,349
and he said it was
something dirty.

163
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:44,350
A sex thing.

164
00:09:44,417 --> 00:09:46,552
Who's Eric Muftie?

165
00:09:46,619 --> 00:09:48,420
A kid in my class.

166
00:09:48,488 --> 00:09:50,522
Well, Eric is wrong.

167
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:52,024
Good.

168
00:09:52,092 --> 00:09:53,726
It's-It's not a...
it's not a sex thing at all.

169
00:09:53,793 --> 00:09:54,727
Good.

170
00:09:54,794 --> 00:09:57,796
It's sort of like a...

171
00:09:57,864 --> 00:09:59,565
Sort of the same
thing as a divorce.

172
00:09:59,632 --> 00:10:01,500
Oh.

173
00:10:01,568 --> 00:10:03,769
You already got one.

174
00:10:05,839 --> 00:10:08,040
You don't really need to worry
about it, okay?

175
00:10:08,108 --> 00:10:09,274
Okay.

176
00:10:09,342 --> 00:10:11,110
I promise you,
Eric is wrong.

177
00:10:11,177 --> 00:10:12,111
Good.

178
00:10:12,178 --> 00:10:13,912
It's not a dirty
thing at all.

179
00:10:13,980 --> 00:10:15,981
Okay.

180
00:10:16,049 --> 00:10:17,182
Here's your letter.

181
00:10:18,518 --> 00:10:20,619
Thanks, Gulls.
Got to get going.

182
00:10:26,993 --> 00:10:28,827
Why can't you just
write to me at home?

183
00:10:28,895 --> 00:10:30,295
Why? You don't
like Mr. Quinette?

184
00:10:30,363 --> 00:10:32,731
He's nice, but sometimes
he isn't there.

185
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:34,299
So I think maybe
I missed one.

186
00:10:34,367 --> 00:10:36,001
No, if there's a
letter, he'll be there.

187
00:10:36,069 --> 00:10:37,736
Okay.

188
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:39,672
I think it's a pretty cool
system, don't you?

189
00:10:39,739 --> 00:10:40,673
I guess.

190
00:10:40,740 --> 00:10:41,674
A secret system.

191
00:10:41,741 --> 00:10:42,808
Yeah.

192
00:10:42,876 --> 00:10:46,111
Gulls, you got to keep it
a secret, okay?

193
00:10:46,179 --> 00:10:47,446
I know.

194
00:10:47,514 --> 00:10:48,947
And after you read
one of my letters,

195
00:10:49,015 --> 00:10:50,449
make sure to just
throw them away, okay?

196
00:10:50,517 --> 00:10:51,984
I do.

197
00:10:52,052 --> 00:10:53,619
Good.

198
00:10:53,687 --> 00:10:54,853
Okay, tell me more.

199
00:10:54,921 --> 00:10:56,855
Are you on a team?
- Yeah.

200
00:10:56,923 --> 00:10:58,023
Soccer, but B team.

201
00:10:58,091 --> 00:10:59,425
What position?
- Left wing.

202
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:00,592
Left wing. Really?

203
00:11:00,660 --> 00:11:01,860
That's pretty hard, right?

204
00:11:01,928 --> 00:11:04,730
